{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458155,"nonce":"WPAK0emiLPjl9TrFPd53ghoVt3o=","title":"Part 2 analysis: steady-state fixed points and Jacobian eigendecomposition","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** Characterize the equilibrium structure of the network when the effector is at the goal (steady state). The Jacobian eigenvalues at these fixed points reveal local stability and time constants, while the input Jacobian SVD reveals how sensitive the network is to different input channels (SISU, position, velocity). Comparing across SISU levels tests whether SISU reorganizes the steady-state attractor landscape.\n\n**Approach:** Find goal-goal fixed points (effector already at target). Compute Jacobians wrt hidden state (eigendecomposition for stability) and wrt inputs (SVD for sensitivity). Applies `get_best_model_replicate` globally before evaluation to save compute. Includes eigenvalue scatter plots, violin plots of eigenvalue magnitude/angle, and singular value distributions.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part2/fps_steady.py`. Most complete of the FP modules: includes `EigvalsPlot`, `process_fps`, steady-state RNN function construction, Jacobian/Hessian computation, and SVD analysis. Uses global `TRANSFORMS` for pre-setup model reduction.\n\n**References:** Sussillo \u0026 Barak (2013); Maheswaranathan et al. (2019) for Jacobian analysis at FPs.","files":null}]}